SIMPLE: smile
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smile
<hw>Smile</hw> <pr>(sm⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Smiled</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦imac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Smiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>smilen</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>smile</ets>, Sw. <ets>smila</ets>,
MHG. <ets>smielen</ets>, <ets>smieren</ets>, L. <ets>mirari</ets> to
wonder at, Skr. <ets>smi</ets> to smile; and probably to E.
<ets>smicker</ets>. ⟦root⟧173. Cf. <er>Admire</er>, <er>Marvel</er>,
<er>Smirk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To express amusement, pleasure,
moderate joy, or love and kindness, by the features of the face; to
laugh silently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He doth nothing but frown. . . . He hears merry tales and
<qex>smiles</qex> not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>smiled</qex> to see the doughty hero slain.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When last I saw thy young blue eyes, they <qex>smiled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express slight contempt by a look implying
sarcasm or pity; to sneer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T was what I said to Craggs and Child,⟦br⟧
Who praised my modesty, and <qex>smiled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To look gay and joyous; to have an appearance suited
to excite joy; <as>as, <ex>smiling</ex> spring; <ex>smiling</ex>
plenty.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The desert <qex>smiled</qex>,⟦br⟧
And paradise was opened in the wild.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be propitious or favorable; to favor; to
countenance; -- often with <xex>on</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>smile</ex> on
one's labors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smile
<hw>Smile</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To express by a smile;
<as>as, to <ex>smile</ex> consent; to <ex>smile</ex> a welcome to
visitors.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To affect in a certain way with a smile.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And sharply <qex>smile</qex> prevailing folly dead.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smile
<hw>Smile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. Dan. <ets>smiil</ets>, Sw.
<ets>smil</ets>. See <er>Smile</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of smiling; a peculiar change or brightening of the face,
which expresses pleasure, moderate joy, mirth, approbation, or kindness;
-- opposed to <contr>frown</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sweet intercourse⟦br⟧
Of looks and <qex>smiles</qex>: for <qex>smiles</qex> from reason
flow.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A somewhat similar expression of countenance,
indicative of satisfaction combined with malevolent feelings, as
contempt, scorn, etc; <as>as, a scornful <ex>smile</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Favor; countenance; propitiousness; <as>as, the
<ex>smiles</ex> of Providence</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>smile</xex> of
heaven.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Gay or joyous appearance; <as>as, the
<ex>smiles</ex> of spring</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The brightness of their [the flowers'] <qex>smile</qex> was
gone.</q> <rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smileless</ent>⟦br⟧
